GIARDIASIS, CANINE - USA (GEORGIA)
**********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 29 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Atlanta Journal Constitution [edited]
<http://www.ajc.com/gwinnett/content/metro/gwinnett/stories/0329gwxpuppies.html>

Six pet stores in metropolotan Atlanta, including the Pet Company store at
the Duluth mall, have been quarantined after a highly infectious parasite
known as giardia, which travels between pets and humans, was found in 138
puppies.
The Duluth store is still open. Staff there said the puppies are being kept
in a kennel behind glass and staff is handling them with precautions,
including changing gloves frequently and washing their hands. Staff said
the puppies, which are on medication, can be purchased, but not touched, by
customers and can only be taken home after they are cleared from
quarantine. They did not specify when that might be.
Store staff referred further questions to the Pet Company headquarters in
New Jersey. A spokesperson there said a statement would be released before
the end of the day and declined to comment further. The statement did not
arrive.
Georgia Department of Agriculture officials warned people who have bought
or touched a puppy from a Pet Company store since January 2006 to contact a
physician if they have flu-like symptoms. According to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, symptoms for giardiasis include: diarrhea,
gas or flatulence, greasy stools, stomach cramps, upset stomach or nausea.
If someone has been infected and is treating the symptoms without the
proper antibiotic, symptoms will recur, Department of Agriculture officials
said.
Department officials said that giardia can be spread by feces and can be
found in drinking and recreational water. They said it's possible the
parasite was transferred if the infected puppies were touched and people
did not wash their hands properly, officials said.
The 6 malls where 138 of 151 puppies tested positive for giardia include:
Gwinnett Place in Duluth, Arbor Place in Douglasville, Southlake Mall in
Morrow, Stonecrest Mall in Lithonia, Town Center Mall in Kennesaw and
Cumberland Mall in Atlanta.
The Department of Agriculture said it has issued a stop sale/stop movement
order for the puppies, so they must remain in the pet stores. Officials
said precautions, such as proper washing of hands, should be taken when
handling the puppies. Department officials said the problem came to light
after a woman bought a puppy in Douglasville in January 2006 and it got sick.
She wasn't satisfied with the response from Pet Company officials and
reported the problem to the Department of Agriculture this month. The
department tested puppies at all Pet Company stores in the metropolitan
Atlanta area.
[byline: Tasgola Karla Bruner]
