[Giardia in dogs in North America has been reported at between and 8 and 50
percent, especially in puppies in shelters, kennels and pet stores. The
prevalence in cats tends to be lower, at about 4 per cent. Most infections
are subclinical or show only transient softening of the stool early in the
infection, although diarrhea may be acute and short-lived, chronic, or
intermittent in dogs and cats.
Treatment for Giardia includes bathing the infected animal and
decontamination of the animalï¿½s environment with a quarternary
ammonium-based disinfectant. Drugs that may be used include metronidazole,
albendazole, fenbendazole, and quanacrine.
GiardiaVax is a commercial Giardia vaccine for use in dogs that may help
prevent infection and reduce the duration of carriage. - Mod.TG]
